    <segment id="1" parent="14" relname="span">
Staying with the credit card example, another inconsistency I run into
frequently is in entering the expiration date.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="12" relname="span"> All of my credit cards
display the expiration date mm/yy</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="condition"> yet invariably if there is a dropdown
box on the form,</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="9" relname="span"> the months are spelled out.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="7" relname="concession"> It&apos;s not a huge issue,</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="10" relname="span"> but
it doesn&apos;t make sense to have the user choose the name of the month
associated with the month number on the credit card.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="8" relname="antithesis"> This is not only
inconsistent with the real world,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="11" relname="span"> it&apos;s an extra step and another place
for a mistake to be made.</segment>
